WEBVTT

00:02.330 --> 00:03.920
Dre:
Children bring so much joy --

00:03.920 --> 00:06.710
except when you have to watch
their school plays.

00:06.710 --> 00:07.880
My name is Diane.

00:07.880 --> 00:09.250
And I'm Jack.

00:09.250 --> 00:11.790
We're in Ms. Davis'
third-grade class.

00:11.790 --> 00:15.000
Years from now, when I look back
on this footage,

00:15.000 --> 00:17.580
I look forward
to hearing you eat mints.

00:17.580 --> 00:18.830
[ Chuckles ]

00:18.830 --> 00:20.000
They're butterscotch.

00:20.000 --> 00:21.120
Mm, okay.
Halfrican.

00:21.120 --> 00:23.380
Uh...
Okay, Ruby.

00:23.380 --> 00:25.000
Well,
can I have one, please?

00:25.000 --> 00:26.540
Mnh-mnh.
It's my last piece.

00:26.540 --> 00:28.000
[ Sighs ]

00:28.000 --> 00:29.580
Can I have one,
Grandma?
She doesn't have
any more.

00:29.580 --> 00:30.790
Well, yes, baby.
What?

00:30.790 --> 00:35.120
I've always got a butterscotch
for family.

00:35.120 --> 00:39.040
In 1492, Columbus sailed
the ocean blue.

00:39.040 --> 00:41.420
[ Scoffs ] Okay.

00:41.420 --> 00:44.000
I'm Christopher Columbus,
and I discovered America.

00:44.000 --> 00:46.830
[ Chuckles ] Okay...

00:46.830 --> 00:48.830
Fake history,
right?

00:48.830 --> 00:52.000
No, I just don't think these
children are that talented.

00:52.000 --> 00:54.000
Is everything okay,
Mr. Johnson?

00:54.000 --> 00:56.120
Do you feel that there's
not enough representation?

00:56.120 --> 00:57.830
Because after
the last incident,

00:57.830 --> 00:59.790
I had children
bussed in.

00:59.790 --> 01:02.380
Honestly,
if I wanted my children

01:02.380 --> 01:04.080
around
this many minorities,

01:04.080 --> 01:06.170
I would have taken them
to a Tyler Perry play

01:06.170 --> 01:07.790
and shamelessly
enjoyed it.

01:07.790 --> 01:08.540
Rainbow: Dre.
Hmm?

01:08.540 --> 01:09.920
Dre.

01:09.920 --> 01:11.250
Can you ask your mom for
a butterscotch for me, please?

01:11.250 --> 01:12.250
Mama --
Unh-unh.

01:12.250 --> 01:13.540
She said no.
Rainbow: What...?

01:13.540 --> 01:15.210
Zoey: You know,
I can drive now,

01:15.210 --> 01:16.830
so we can just leave
and never come back here.

01:16.830 --> 01:18.420
[ Scoffs ]

01:18.420 --> 01:21.420
And miss the moment
when Mom decides to divorce Dad

01:21.420 --> 01:23.790
and we sneak out
under the cover of night

01:23.790 --> 01:27.790
to start a new life,
opening an artisanal coffee shop

01:27.790 --> 01:31.540
in a transitioning but scrappy
neighborhood in Portland?

01:31.540 --> 01:33.540
[ Piano playing ]

01:33.540 --> 01:36.040
Dre: Ms. Davis, you should be
ashamed of yourself.

01:36.040 --> 01:38.080
Where you really failed

01:38.080 --> 01:41.040
is this isn't
how it went down.

01:41.040 --> 01:43.580
[ Rapping ] ♪ Everything you
know about Columbus is a joke ♪

01:43.580 --> 01:45.120
♪ He didn't
discover America ♪

01:45.120 --> 01:46.540
♪ Prepare to get woke ♪

01:46.540 --> 01:48.960
♪ I'm Christopher Columbus,
and I'm pretty much evil ♪

01:48.960 --> 01:51.830
♪ On Hispaniola, my men killed
the indigenous people ♪

01:51.830 --> 01:53.540
Die, Indians!

01:53.540 --> 01:54.790
But this isn't India!

01:54.790 --> 01:56.670
Speak English!
[ Pop! ]

01:56.670 --> 01:58.880
[ Grunts ]

01:58.880 --> 02:01.330
♪ You're so brave,
Columbus ♪

02:01.330 --> 02:02.880
♪ More than words
can convey ♪

02:02.880 --> 02:05.580
♪ And it's cool how your men
killed 3,000 people in one day ♪

02:05.580 --> 02:07.790
♪ So let's make one thing
perfectly clear ♪

02:07.790 --> 02:11.000
♪ Celebrating Columbus is
celebrating a slavery pioneer ♪

02:11.000 --> 02:14.880
But at least you can get
a great deal on a mattress.

02:14.880 --> 02:16.580
[ Piano playing ]
[ Inhales sharply ]

02:16.580 --> 02:21.080
We will take your opinions
into consideration.

02:21.080 --> 02:23.210
Hmm.
Well, instead of making us
celebrate your holidays,

02:23.210 --> 02:24.620
why don't you celebrate
some of ours?

02:24.620 --> 02:26.380
Hmm.
Everybody is
represented here.

02:26.380 --> 02:27.580
St. Patrick's Day.

02:27.580 --> 02:28.960
Columbus Day.
Mm-hmm.

02:28.960 --> 02:30.500
Cinco de Mayo.
Yeah.

02:30.500 --> 02:33.170
What about
2Pac's birthday?
Oh, well --

02:33.170 --> 02:35.000
What about Magic Johnson's
Still Alive Day?
Really?

02:35.000 --> 02:36.210
[ People murmuring ]
Earl.

02:36.210 --> 02:37.580
What about Juneteenth?

02:37.580 --> 02:40.120
Maybe you should have led
with that last one.

02:40.120 --> 02:41.210
Maybe.
Okay.

02:41.210 --> 02:42.830
[ Piano playing ]

02:42.830 --> 02:44.880
I offer this to you
in peace.

02:44.880 --> 02:46.380
Dre:
Mm, mm, mm.

02:46.380 --> 02:50.290
I can't believe you would honor
a slave trader like Columbus

02:50.290 --> 02:53.000
when you do not
honor Juneteenth --

02:53.000 --> 02:55.540
a proud black holiday tradition
that my family treasures!

02:55.540 --> 02:57.460
What?
We don't celebrate Juneteenth --

02:57.460 --> 02:59.830
Shut up, Junior!
You love it.

02:59.830 --> 03:01.290
[ People murmuring ]
It's very important
in our household.

03:01.290 --> 03:03.500
Johnsons,
we about to be out.

03:03.500 --> 03:05.080
Excuse me!

03:05.080 --> 03:06.000
[ People gasping, murmuring ]

03:06.000 --> 03:07.460
Here we go again.

03:07.460 --> 03:10.830
I hope you enjoy the rest
of your racist pageant.

03:10.830 --> 03:12.170
[ People gasping ]
Johnsons!

03:12.170 --> 03:13.040
We out!
No, no, no, no!

03:13.040 --> 03:14.620
That --
That's not true!

03:14.620 --> 03:17.120
30% of the cast
are colored children!

03:17.120 --> 03:18.250
Rainbow: Okay.

03:18.250 --> 03:19.620
Children of color.

03:19.620 --> 03:20.580
That was not great.

03:20.580 --> 03:21.670
♪♪

03:21.670 --> 03:23.170
[ Groans ]

03:23.170 --> 03:24.540
Hi.

03:24.540 --> 03:27.210
So, we just want to thank you
for the minorities.

03:27.210 --> 03:28.670
We can tell
you're trying,

03:28.670 --> 03:30.920
and it means
a lot to us.
Thank you.

03:30.920 --> 03:32.420
Okay.
See you, now.
But --

03:32.420 --> 03:34.170
Listen, I have
a great eyebrow person.

03:34.170 --> 03:35.710
[ Chuckles, groans ]

03:35.710 --> 03:37.670
Huh?
What does that mean?

03:37.670 --> 03:39.000
What?!

03:39.000 --> 03:41.830
[ Laughing ]
I look fine!

03:41.830 --> 03:43.830
[ Laughing ]

03:50.500 --> 03:52.960
I realized
that for Juneteenth to live,

03:52.960 --> 03:55.790
Columbus Day had to die,
so it was up to me.

03:55.790 --> 03:58.380
Well, me and Grammy-nominated
Aloe Blacc.

03:58.380 --> 03:59.960
Okay,
you know the drill, man.

03:59.960 --> 04:02.000
You get lunch
when you make me a hit.

04:02.000 --> 04:03.580
All right, let's take it again
from the top.

04:03.580 --> 04:05.000
Come on.

04:05.000 --> 04:06.790
♪ Everybody knows ♪

04:06.790 --> 04:10.670
♪ Christopher Columbus
was honored for his bravery ♪

04:10.670 --> 04:12.790
♪ But he never sailed
to North America ♪

04:12.790 --> 04:15.120
♪ He sold children
into slavery ♪

04:15.120 --> 04:16.790
Mm!

04:16.790 --> 04:19.000
Stevens: That does not
sound like an ad for Samsung.

04:19.000 --> 04:20.750
Nope,
I'm using Aloe Blacc

04:20.750 --> 04:23.380
to put an end
to Columbus Day.

04:23.380 --> 04:25.120
You're why black people
can't get jobs.

04:25.120 --> 04:26.380
Well, that's one
of many reasons.

04:26.380 --> 04:27.580
Dre:
I'm serious.

04:27.580 --> 04:29.920
Columbus Day
is a BS holiday.

04:29.920 --> 04:31.880
Okay, so I guess you'll be
at work on Monday.
Oh.

04:31.880 --> 04:33.920
You sound stupid.

04:33.920 --> 04:35.500
Okay?
Did you know

04:35.500 --> 04:39.170
that Columbus never even
set foot in North America?

04:39.170 --> 04:41.120
What?
Prove it.
Yes, he did.

04:41.120 --> 04:42.120
Come on, now.
Fake news.

04:42.120 --> 04:43.580
The only reason
we celebrate dude

04:43.580 --> 04:46.120
is 'cause everyone remembers
that hook, "In 1492..."

04:46.120 --> 04:48.000
All: "Columbus sailed
the ocean blue."

04:48.000 --> 04:49.540
Yeah, yeah, yeah.
Charlie: Mm-hmm.

04:49.540 --> 04:51.750
First I'm hearing
about this Columbo fellow.

04:51.750 --> 04:53.210
What?

04:53.210 --> 04:54.620
I spent my time
in school

04:54.620 --> 04:57.170
learning a trade
way more valuable than any book.

04:57.170 --> 04:58.960
I learned
how to forge résumés,

04:58.960 --> 05:01.000
college diplomas,
time sheets.

05:04.880 --> 05:06.790
I've said too much.

05:06.790 --> 05:10.170
The point is
we celebrate a horrible man

05:10.170 --> 05:12.170
when we don't even
acknowledge

05:12.170 --> 05:13.960
important moments
in our own history,

05:13.960 --> 05:15.290
like Juneteenth.

05:15.290 --> 05:16.380
Oh!
What is June--
No, no, no, no, no.

05:16.380 --> 05:17.380
Daphne:
Oh, my God!

05:17.380 --> 05:18.670
No!
No, no, no, no.

05:18.670 --> 05:20.540
...teenth?
Damn it!
There goes lunch!

05:20.540 --> 05:24.830
All right, June 19, 1865,
or "Juneteenth,"

05:24.830 --> 05:28.080
is the day in America where
all slaves were finally free.

05:28.080 --> 05:31.080
You did this.
You.

05:31.080 --> 05:33.120
And on that fateful day
in history --

05:33.120 --> 05:34.580
Aloe Blacc:
Actually...

05:34.580 --> 05:36.750
maybe Juneteenth is
better explained through song.

05:36.750 --> 05:37.750
Oh.

05:37.750 --> 05:39.330
Dre: Oh. Okay.

05:39.330 --> 05:41.790
You know, I usually give
the history lessons around here,

05:41.790 --> 05:43.380
but go ahead,
Aloe Blacc.

05:43.380 --> 05:44.670
You know,
I'll just sit here.

05:44.670 --> 05:46.080
[ Keyboard playing ]

05:46.080 --> 05:55.750
♪♪

05:55.750 --> 05:57.580
♪ I am a slave ♪

05:57.580 --> 05:59.620
♪ Yes, I'm only a slave ♪

05:59.620 --> 06:02.580
♪ They'll place my body
in an unmarked grave ♪

06:02.580 --> 06:04.830
♪ In these Confederate days ♪

06:04.830 --> 06:08.210
♪ It's kind of hard
to lift every voice singin' ♪

06:08.210 --> 06:09.580
♪ While worrying about how low ♪

06:09.580 --> 06:12.210
♪ The sweet chariots
are swingin' ♪

06:12.210 --> 06:13.830
♪ I could swing from a tree ♪

06:13.830 --> 06:17.790
♪ But, hey, oh, I hope and pray
they don't kill me ♪

06:17.790 --> 06:22.500
♪ Today
I am still just a slave ♪

06:22.500 --> 06:26.210
If the Emancipation Proclamation
was passed in 1863,

06:26.210 --> 06:28.620
why weren't you free
until 1865?

06:28.620 --> 06:31.580
Well, it took two years
for the Civil War to end.

06:31.580 --> 06:33.540
Oh, so you were free
when the war ended?

06:33.540 --> 06:35.170
Nah, not for
two more months

06:35.170 --> 06:37.960
because Texas landowners
wanted another harvest.

06:37.960 --> 06:39.120
That's not cool.

06:39.120 --> 06:40.580
Well,
none of it was cool.

06:40.580 --> 06:43.960
But an army ship arrived
on June 19, 1865,

06:43.960 --> 06:45.000
and announced
we were free.

06:45.000 --> 06:46.750
That's why we celebrate
Juneteenth.

06:46.750 --> 06:47.960
♪♪

06:47.960 --> 06:50.000
♪ I am a slave ♪

06:50.000 --> 06:52.000
♪ In the home of the brave ♪

06:52.000 --> 06:54.790
♪ A product
of the triangular trade ♪

06:54.790 --> 06:57.000
♪ Please pardon my ways ♪

06:57.000 --> 07:00.420
♪ If I'm nervous
or the slightest bit skittish ♪

07:00.420 --> 07:02.380
♪ In the presence
of the Portuguese ♪

07:02.380 --> 07:04.000
♪ Spanish, Dutch, or British ♪

07:04.000 --> 07:06.540
♪ They kept me
in colonial chains ♪

07:06.540 --> 07:09.790
♪ Tell me
how to persuade them to chill ♪

07:09.790 --> 07:13.540
♪ Or to save me,
and still I'm a slave ♪

07:13.540 --> 07:22.080
♪♪

07:28.250 --> 07:30.540
That was not uncomfortable
at all.

07:30.540 --> 07:32.580
Nope.

07:32.580 --> 07:34.120
Is that stuff true,
Papa?

07:38.460 --> 07:39.830
Just like
anything black people do,

07:39.830 --> 07:41.290
if Juneteenth
had a chance of succeeding,

07:41.290 --> 07:42.620
we would have to brand
and market it twice as hard.

07:42.620 --> 07:44.620
What do you think
of this Juneteenth mock-up?

07:44.620 --> 07:46.000
Hold on.

07:46.000 --> 07:47.830
Did you take
my egg rolls?

07:47.830 --> 07:49.790
[ Garbled ]
These aren't for the table?

07:49.790 --> 07:50.830
They were not.

07:52.790 --> 07:54.420
Stevens:
Really, Dre?

07:54.420 --> 07:55.920
I figured
this was one of those things

07:55.920 --> 07:57.210
that you would just
get tired of,

07:57.210 --> 07:58.790
like kente cloth.

07:58.790 --> 08:06.170
♪♪

08:07.670 --> 08:09.540
This isn't a trend,
all right?

08:09.540 --> 08:11.920
Juneteenth is
a 150-year-old tradition

08:11.920 --> 08:13.500
that no one's
heard about,

08:13.500 --> 08:15.170
not even
my black kids.

08:15.170 --> 08:17.080
I mean, there's --
there's storytelling.

08:17.080 --> 08:19.500
There's red-velvet cake,
hibiscus tea.

08:19.500 --> 08:22.120
Actually, hibiscus tea
is a modern-day substitute

08:22.120 --> 08:23.420
for strawberry soda.

08:23.420 --> 08:24.620
Oh, really?
That's interesting.

08:24.620 --> 08:27.040
Really?!
Never had it.
I didn't know that.

08:27.040 --> 08:28.250
Thank you,
Aloe Blacc,

08:28.250 --> 08:29.580
for correcting me
in front of company.

08:29.580 --> 08:30.830
Okay?

08:30.830 --> 08:32.620
Josh: Hey, Dre,
I don't get it.

08:32.620 --> 08:34.670
I mean, don't you
already have MLK day?

08:34.670 --> 08:36.290
And Black History Month?

08:36.290 --> 08:38.120
And Reparations Day.

08:38.120 --> 08:39.830
That's when
in times of civil unrest,

08:39.830 --> 08:41.460
we start urban bonfires

08:41.460 --> 08:43.750
and acquire
discount electronics.

08:43.750 --> 08:45.670
Charlie, are you
talking about looting?

08:45.670 --> 08:47.500
That's just looting.
Connor: Yeah.

08:47.500 --> 08:49.540
The truth is
we don't have anything

08:49.540 --> 08:51.880
that celebrates
the end of slavery.

08:51.880 --> 08:54.750
Stevens: Well, MLK Day is a
pretty big umbrella there, Dre.

08:54.750 --> 08:56.290
Like,
Mary Poppins big.

08:56.290 --> 08:57.540
[ Chuckles ]

08:57.540 --> 08:58.790
This is insane.

08:58.790 --> 09:01.250
You don't tell white people
or Jewish people

09:01.250 --> 09:03.540
that they only deserve
one holiday.

09:03.540 --> 09:05.620
Connor: Well, half that
statement's true. [ Chuckles ]

09:05.620 --> 09:07.210
It just seems, Dre, like you're
getting a little bit greedy.

09:08.330 --> 09:09.420
For real?!

09:09.420 --> 09:10.920
Yeah.
You guys
are giving push-back

09:10.920 --> 09:14.210
on the one thing that honors
the end of slavery?

09:14.210 --> 09:16.960
You do know why
America's so rich, right?

09:16.960 --> 09:20.250
Because we built this land
for free.

09:20.250 --> 09:26.170
♪♪

09:26.170 --> 09:28.210
Mama?
Yeah, baby?

09:28.210 --> 09:29.960
Can you
tell us a story?

09:29.960 --> 09:31.290
Of course I can.

09:31.290 --> 09:33.330
Baby, what kind of story
you want to hear?

09:33.330 --> 09:35.210
Um, tell us
a scary story.
Mm.

09:35.210 --> 09:37.790
No, no, no,
tell us a love story.

09:37.790 --> 09:40.540
Ooh! Tell us a story about
a slave who gets free!
Junior!

09:40.540 --> 09:41.920
Say what?
Ruby:
Oh, my God!

09:41.920 --> 09:43.540
W-What did you...?

09:44.210 --> 09:46.120
Boy, what is wrong
with you?

09:46.120 --> 09:49.250
You see, them light-skinned
babies never know how to act.

09:49.250 --> 09:52.210
Here's a story
won't get us all killed.

09:52.210 --> 09:55.380
How we built this country
for free.

09:56.830 --> 10:03.670
[ Choir vocalizing ]

10:03.670 --> 10:06.710
[ Hip-hop beat plays ]

10:06.710 --> 10:13.580
♪♪

10:13.580 --> 10:15.830
[ Baby crying ]

10:15.830 --> 10:20.210
♪ Oh, oh, oh, oh ♪

10:20.210 --> 10:22.380
More quick.

10:22.380 --> 10:25.920
♪♪

10:25.920 --> 10:28.380
It's gonna be okay.

10:28.380 --> 10:30.830
It's gonna be all right.

10:30.830 --> 10:33.380
♪ We raised
their children ♪

10:33.380 --> 10:35.580
♪ Then raised
their buildings ♪

10:35.580 --> 10:38.210
♪ And they made billions ♪

10:38.210 --> 10:40.960
♪ I'm catching feelings ♪

10:40.960 --> 10:44.040
♪ Really?
What else did we build? ♪

10:44.040 --> 10:45.210
♪ Railroads ♪

10:45.210 --> 10:46.380
♪ Wall Street ♪

10:46.380 --> 10:48.750
♪ The White House
and university ♪

10:48.750 --> 10:49.880
♪ UVA? ♪

10:49.880 --> 10:51.170
♪ We built that ♪

10:51.170 --> 10:52.170
♪ Chapel Hill? ♪

10:52.170 --> 10:53.330
♪ We built that ♪

10:53.330 --> 10:54.830
♪ Pyramids? ♪

10:54.830 --> 10:58.000
♪ No, sorry, our Hebrew brothers
get credit for that ♪

10:58.000 --> 11:00.210
♪ Mazel ♪

11:00.210 --> 11:03.580
♪ Let's turn up
and get it poppin' ♪

11:03.580 --> 11:04.790
♪ Settle down ♪

11:04.790 --> 11:06.880
♪ We still
ain't got nothin' ♪

11:06.880 --> 11:09.290
♪ We built this ♪

11:09.290 --> 11:15.790
♪ Oh, oh, oh, oh, oh ♪

11:15.790 --> 11:18.380
♪ We built this ♪

11:18.380 --> 11:25.040
♪ Oh, oh, oh, oh, oh ♪

11:25.040 --> 11:25.920
♪ I'm done, y'all ♪

11:25.920 --> 11:27.540
♪ I'm-a keep it 100 ♪

11:27.540 --> 11:29.790
♪ Tomorrow when I hit the field,
I'm-a keep runnin' ♪

11:29.790 --> 11:31.920
♪ We did everything
that the overseer wanted ♪

11:31.920 --> 11:34.170
♪ And if we got paid,
then we'd be stuntin' ♪

11:34.170 --> 11:36.540
♪ Sugarcane,
cotton hands ♪

11:36.540 --> 11:38.580
♪ My blood and sweat
paid for this land ♪

11:38.580 --> 11:40.790
♪ My life
would have been different ♪

11:40.790 --> 11:42.750
♪ If I didn't have
cinnamon pigment ♪

11:42.750 --> 11:45.790
♪ We built this ♪

11:47.540 --> 11:48.830
Josh: Wait.

11:48.830 --> 11:50.790
You don't think
my grandparents' summer house

11:50.790 --> 11:53.170
in Savannah, Georgia,
was built by slaves, do you?

11:53.170 --> 11:54.620
Oh,
i-it's so beautiful.

11:54.620 --> 11:57.000
There's this big house,
and then there's all these

11:57.000 --> 11:59.420
little play houses
out back -- Oh!

11:59.420 --> 12:01.120
Oh, no.
Daphne: Yep.

12:01.120 --> 12:02.500
Every Thanksgiving,

12:02.500 --> 12:05.460
you felt up your cousin
in slave quarters.

12:05.460 --> 12:08.620
Only before she got married
and after her divorce.

12:08.620 --> 12:10.250
A-And last week.

12:10.250 --> 12:13.920
You've never truly loved
until you loved your cousin.

12:13.920 --> 12:15.290
She's my first cousin.

12:15.290 --> 12:17.250
Doesn't matter.
Thank you.

12:17.250 --> 12:18.580
Dre:
The point is

12:18.580 --> 12:21.210
black people don't get
the credit that we deserve

12:21.210 --> 12:23.290
for working
hundreds of years.

12:23.290 --> 12:26.170
You can never put a number
on the amount of wealth

12:26.170 --> 12:28.250
that we've created
for this country.

12:28.250 --> 12:30.380
Actually,
social scientists estimate

12:30.380 --> 12:31.670
that slaves contributed

12:31.670 --> 12:33.540
$300 billion worth
of economic value.

12:33.540 --> 12:35.380
What?!
Dre: Seriously?
Stevens: Whoa!

12:35.380 --> 12:36.670
Dre: Seriously?
Wow!

12:36.670 --> 12:37.830
Seriously?

12:37.830 --> 12:40.580
Aloe Blacc,
you are a guest at my work.

12:40.580 --> 12:42.330
I don't show up
at your job

12:42.330 --> 12:45.250
and vaguely sound like
Tracy Chapman.

12:45.250 --> 12:46.880
I'm doing you
a favor.

12:46.880 --> 12:48.380
Connor: Dre.
Brah?

12:48.380 --> 12:51.040
Aloe Blacc has convinced us
slavery was a bad thing.

12:51.040 --> 12:53.000
Yeah, so thank you
for that, Aloe.

12:53.000 --> 12:55.540
I'm just saying, Dre,
that maybe it's healthier

12:55.540 --> 12:58.290
for you to put
all this negativity behind you.

12:58.290 --> 12:59.500
Your people --

12:59.500 --> 13:01.790
Well, they have been free
for a long time.

13:01.790 --> 13:03.040
Long time.

13:03.040 --> 13:04.120
Dre: Really?
Yeah.

13:04.120 --> 13:06.250
You think
we're free?

13:06.250 --> 13:10.000
Your tone makes me feel
this is a trick question.

13:10.000 --> 13:12.750
Things just didn't get better
on June 20th.

13:12.750 --> 13:15.330
Even when we were free,
we weren't free.

13:15.330 --> 13:16.500
[ All cheering ]

13:16.500 --> 13:18.000
Free!
We're free!

13:18.000 --> 13:19.670
We're free!
We're free!

13:19.670 --> 13:20.750
[ Laughs ]

13:20.750 --> 13:21.790
Come here!

13:21.790 --> 13:23.170
[ Both laugh ]

13:23.170 --> 13:24.790
Get over here!
[ Laughs ]

13:24.790 --> 13:26.960
We're free!
So, what happens now?

13:26.960 --> 13:28.540
Oh, we're free,
dummy!

13:28.540 --> 13:30.620
Okay, but what
does that mean?

13:30.620 --> 13:32.330
Well, it's...

13:32.330 --> 13:34.380
Pops.
Ruby: Yeah.

13:34.380 --> 13:35.790
What does that mean?

13:35.790 --> 13:37.790
What do you think
it means, dummy?! We're free.

13:37.790 --> 13:39.210
We're free to do
whatever we want!

13:39.210 --> 13:40.210
Whoo!
Ohh!

13:40.210 --> 13:41.580
Diane: Then can I
ride a horse?

13:41.580 --> 13:42.790
Absolutely, baby!

13:42.790 --> 13:44.120
Can I buy
strawberry soda?

13:44.120 --> 13:45.420
Yeah!

13:45.420 --> 13:46.750
Yeah, but you gonna have to
get in line behind me.

13:46.750 --> 13:47.750
Oh!

13:47.750 --> 13:49.040
Can I be president?!

13:49.040 --> 13:50.380
Whoa, whoa!
Hey, hey, now.

13:50.380 --> 13:51.380
Settle down.

13:51.380 --> 13:52.620
Oh!
That's your son.

13:52.620 --> 13:54.580
Okay, I got it, Pops.
Listen here, son.

13:54.580 --> 13:55.920
Being free

13:55.920 --> 13:59.790
means we're finally
gonna be equal to the white man.

